  "text": "## Chromium Renderer Process Sandbox Audit Findings\n\nThis audit identified the key C++ source files implementing Chromium's renderer process sandbox:\n\n### 1. Linux seccomp-BPF Baseline Policy\n**File:** `sandbox/linux/seccomp-bpf-helpers/baseline_policy.h` (GitHub, sg-evals/chromium--2d05e315)\n**Class:** `BaselinePolicy` (line 27) - implements the seccomp-BPF baseline policy for Linux sandboxing\n**Key Method:** `EvaluateSyscall(int system_call_number)` (line 39) - evaluates which syscalls are allowed\n**Parent:** Extends `bpf_dsl::Policy`\n**Implementation:** `sandbox/linux/seccomp-bpf-helpers/baseline_policy.cc`\n\nThe BaselinePolicy is the foundation for all Chromium sandbox policies on Linux. It's \"implementation-defined\" but represents a reasonable common ground to run most code in a sandboxed environment. The policy is only valid for the process that instantiates it.\n\n### 2. Windows Sandbox Policy Configuration\n**File:** `sandbox/win/src/sandbox_policy_base.h` (GitHub, sg-evals/chromium--2d05e315)\n**Class:** `PolicyBase` (line 165) - concrete implementation of `TargetPolicy` interface\n**Key Methods:** \n  - `GetConfig()` (line 174) - returns the TargetConfig for this policy\n  - `InitJob()` (line 182) - creates a Job object with the configured level\n  - `MakeTokens()` (line 197) - creates tokens with specified levels\n  - `ApplyToTarget()` (line 202) - applies the sandbox to target process\n**Implementation:** `sandbox/win/src/sandbox_policy_base.cc`\n\nPolicyBase is the primary class for Windows sandbox configuration. It's paired with ConfigBase which holds the actual configuration data. PolicyBase manages per-process configuration including token levels, job levels, process mitigations, and app container profiles.\n\n### 3. Renderer Process BPF Policy\n**File:** `sandbox/policy/linux/bpf_renderer_policy_linux.h` (GitHub, sg-evals/chromium--2d05e315)\n**Class:** `RendererProcessPolicy` (line 19) - BPF policy specific to renderer process sandboxing\n**Key Method:** `EvaluateSyscall(int system_call_number)` (line 33) - evaluates renderer-specific syscall allowances\n**Parent:** Extends `BPFBasePolicy`\n**Implementation:** `sandbox/policy/linux/bpf_renderer_policy_linux.cc`\n\nThe RendererProcessPolicy extends the baseline policy with renderer-specific syscall rules. It can be used by both renderer and worker processes. On Android, it accepts BaselinePolicyAndroid::RuntimeOptions for additional configuration.\n\n### 4. Sandbox Type Enumeration and Utilities\n**File 1:** `sandbox/policy/sandbox_type.h` (GitHub, sg-evals/chromium--2d05e315)\nDeclares utility functions:\n  - `IsUnsandboxedSandboxType()` - checks if a sandbox type runs unsandboxed\n  - `SetCommandLineFlagsForSandboxType()` - applies sandbox-specific command line flags\n  - `SandboxTypeFromCommandLine()` - parses sandbox type from command line\n  - `StringFromUtilitySandboxType()` / `UtilitySandboxTypeFromString()` - string conversions\n\nReferences the `sandbox::mojom::Sandbox` enum (forward declaration at line 15).\n\n**File 2:** `sandbox/policy/mojom/sandbox.mojom` (GitHub, sg-evals/chromium--2d05e315)\nDefines the `Sandbox` enum (line 13) with all sandbox types including:\n  - `kNoSandbox` (line 50) - runs with browser rights\n  - `kRenderer` (line 62) - hosts untrustworthy web content with maximum OS access restrictions\n  - `kGpu` (line 54) - GPU service access\n  - `kService` / `kServiceWithJit` - computation-only services\n  - `kUtility` - generic utilities with limited system access\n  - Multiple platform-specific types (macOS, Windows, ChromeOS, Fuchsia)\n\nThis mojom file is the canonical definition of all sandbox types used throughout Chromium's process isolation system.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe Chromium sandbox audit reveals a layered architecture:\n- **Linux:** BaselinePolicy (seccomp-BPF) → RendererProcessPolicy (renderer-specific rules)\n- **Windows:** PolicyBase manages per-process configuration with ConfigBase for shared settings\n- **Cross-platform:** SandboxType enumeration coordinates sandbox type selection and utilities across all platforms\n\nThe renderer process is the most restrictive sandbox, designed to isolate untrusted web content from the browser process and OS resources."
}

